[TOKYO DISNEY](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/tokyo-disney/)\n  * [TOKYO WITHOUT KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/tokyo-without-kids/)\n  * [OTHER JAPANESE CITIES](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/other-cities/)\n    * [KYOTO WITH KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/kyoto-with-kids/)\n  * [FLYING WITH KIDS & BABIES](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/flying-with-kids-and-babies/)\n  * [OTHER COUNTRIES WITH KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/other-countries-with-kids/)\n  * [ITINERARIES BY ME](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/category/itineraries-by-me/)\n  * [](https://www.instagram.com/thetokyochapter/ \"Instagram\")[](https://www.pinterest.jp/thetokyochapter/ \"Pinterest\")[](https://www.facebook.com/thetokyochapter/ \"Facebook\")\n  * \n\n[Jo](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/author/johannamacgregorgmail-com/ \"Posts by Jo\") April 6, 2026\n# FREE THINGS TO DO IN TOKYO WITH KIDS\n![FREE THINGS TO DO IN TOKYO WITH KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/happoen-5-year-old-lucy-1440x1440.jpg)\nWhen I plan time in Tokyo with kids, I plan for 1 thing for adults to be mixed with 3 fun things for children. But it’s always ideal if those things don’t cost a thing.  \n[I’ve also written advice on how to keep costs down when traveling in Japan here. ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/how-to-keep-costs-down-in-japan/)  \n[See here for the lower priced accommodation options in Tokyo for families here.](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)\nHere are my suggestions:\n**Amazing Tokyo Retro Playgrounds**  \nI have a gigantic [list of retro Tokyo playgrounds **here**.](https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&q=the+tokyo+chapter+retro&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8) Most of them are free to enter too.  \nFor example ( see the full list for addresses and access details) :\n[**The Dinosaur Park**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/dinosaur-playground-shinagawa/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/dino-park-2-800x800.jpg) Dinosaur Playground in Shinagawa\n**[The Pig Park in Setagaya](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/breakfast-plum-blossoms-park/)**\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/pig-park-face-800x800.jpg) the Pig Park\n**[Asukayama Park in Kita-ku](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/asukayama-park-kita-ku-tokyo/)**  \nEasiest way to get there with kids? Take the Yamanote to Otsuka Station and then just grab a taxi from the taxi rank for 12 mins!\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/collageasukayama-800x450.jpg) Asukayama Park.\n**Where to eat with kids near Asukayama Park?**  \nJust 3 mins walk from the park is an incredible family friendly restaurant called **Apronmark.** They accept most major credit cards. They have a kids menu and free baby food. They also have picture books for children to read. They are happy for diners to enter the restaurant with strollers. I recommend budgeting 2000 yen for an adult meal for lunch and more like 5000 yen at dinner time. This restaurant can be busy on weekends and sunny days so it might be a good idea to make a reservation. [See images of menu items here. ](https://www.instagram.com/apronmark_asukayama?igshid=YmMyMTA2M2Y%3D)  \n**APRONMARK  \n** 北区西ケ原2-16-2 飛鳥山公園  \nASUKAYAMA PARK, 2-16-2 NISHIGAHARA, KITA-KU  \nOPEN 11AM-4PM & 5PM-9PM (LAST ORDERS AN HOUR BEFORE CLOSING TIME) * OPEN UNTIL 10PM ON FRI & SAT NIGHT  \nCLOSED MONDAYS & EVERY 1ST AND 3RD TUESDAY OF THE MONTH  \n\n**[Robot Park in Roppongi](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/robot-park-roppongi/)** <- Link to my full article on this park here.\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/robot-park-800x800.jpg) Robot Park, Roppongi.\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/roppongi-robot-2-800x800.jpg) Robot Park in Roppongi\n_*If you are strictly**gluten free** – before or after Robot Park – go to one of the restaurants at the nearby Grand Hyatt Tokyo, Roppongi, for a meal. They are great at assisting those who need a strictly gluten free meal._\n**Free Museums**  \nThe Police Museum ( [I wrote all about the Tokyo Police Museum here](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/tokyo-police-museum-ginza/) )  \nIt’s open earlier than a lot of other Tokyo Museums too!  \n_**Please note that the Police Museum in Ginza is currently closed (as of Sept 15, 2025)  \nIt will be opening in a new location, Shinagawa, in 2026.**_\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/police-museum-abbie-800x927.jpg) Police Museum, Ginza\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/police-museum-9-800x800.jpg) Police Museum, Ginza\nThe Fire Museum just out of Shinjuku[ (detailed post on the Fire Museum in Shinjuku with kids here.)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/fire-museum-shinjuku/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/collagefiremuseum-800x450.jpg) The Fire Museum (Free)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/collagefiremuseum2-800x450.jpg) The Fire Museum \n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fire-museum-3-800x600.jpg) Fire Museum\n**Tokyo Gas Science Museum  \n**(6 mins walk from Team Lab Planets) **  \n**I haven’t visited yet but many parents tell me that this museum is excellent and very interactive for little ones. Entry is free and there is no need for a reservation. Open 9:30am-5pm (last entry at 4:30pm)\n**Tokyo Water Science Museum**  \n(20 mins walk or 11 mins – approx 1500 yen – by taxi from[ Team Lab Planets](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/team-lab-dmm-planets/))   \nTokyo Water Science Museum is free and although most of the exhibits are labelled in Japanese they are interactive button pushing type activities – which kids love.  \nPlease note that the Tokyo Water Science Museum is closed on Mondays. Every other day they are open from 9:30am – 5pm (4;30pm is last entry.) Entry is free.\nCool things to see ( and take photos with)  \nGo and spot Godzilla from the ground and up close in Shinjuku. Details [**here.**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/the-ginza-area-with-kids/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/godzilla-shinjuku-800x800.jpg) The Godzilla Statue in Shinjuku\n**Free Shrines & Temples**  \nThere is Meiji Shrine in Harajuku ( it is best on weekends as you may be fortunate enough to witness at Japanese wedding.) Warning – it is quite a walk up to the entrance so little legs will most likely need a stroller.  \nThe details are in my Harajuku with Kids post [**here.**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/the-harajuku-omotesando-area-with-kids/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/collagemeiji-800x450.jpg) Meiji Jingu Shrine\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/meiji-wedding-800x534.jpg) Meiji Jingu Shrine\nThe Lucky Cat Shrine, Setagaya (details can be found in my ‘A More Traditional Japan without leaving Tokyo’ post [**here.**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/a-more-traditional-japan-without-leaving-tokyo/))\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/cat-shrine-kids-touching-800x800.jpg) The Lucky Cat Shrine in Tokyo\n**Hie Shrine, Akasaka.**  \nAll of the details are in my Akasaka with kids post [**here.**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/the-akasaka-area-with-kids/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/hie-me-800x800.jpg)[![Pin this image on Pinterest](https://pipdigz.co.uk/p3/img/pin/black_circle.png)](https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button?url=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/&media=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thetokyochapter.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2018%2F04%2Fhie-me-800x800.jpg&description=%20FREE%20THINGS%20TO%20DO%20IN%20TOKYO%20WITH%20KIDS)\nHie Shrine\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/hie-exterior-800x800.jpg)[![Pin this image on Pinterest](https://pipdigz.co.uk/p3/img/pin/black_circle.png)](https://www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button?url=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/&media=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thetokyochapter.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2018%2F04%2Fhie-exterior-800x800.jpg&description=%20FREE%20THINGS%20TO%20DO%20IN%20TOKYO%20WITH%20KIDS)\nHie Shrine\n**Tokyo Parks**  \nA run around in **Yoyogi Park** is also free.  \nA huge park (no playground equipment) and a lovely slice of green in the middle of the busy city. Like all large, beautiful parks in Japan, the foliage and view is completely different with every season.  \nThe cafe near the entrance sells some savoury snacks and sweets as well as outdoor toys such as wind-up planes, frisbees and bubble liquid and wands. There are lots of vending machines and public restrooms. The pond in the middle has ducks and lots of big trees make for great hide’n’seek sessions. If you have a kite or a scooter – this is one of the best central parks for it (some other parks have funny rules about sporting equipment etc.)  \n  \n**And this is not free but it’s ALMOST FREE…..**  \n**Did you know that you can now rent a bike in Yoyogi Park (including kids bikes, tandem bikes and parent & child _mamachari_ electric bikes in Yoyogi Park with prices starting at 100 yen? **(they accept most major credit cards, including Diners Club and American Express!)   \nTo rent bikes as a family in Yoyogi Park, put “Yoyogi Park Cycling Center” into google maps (also sometimes referred to as “Pedalico”) – closest station is Yoyogi Park Station Exit 4B but you can also walk from Harajuku easily. Helmet rental is also available. The smallest child sized bike is a 12 inch (for children 2-4 years) and the Parent Child bikes are for children up to   \n_Please note that bikes can only be used within Yoyogi Park grounds._ The Cycling Center in Yoyogi is open 9am-4:30pm and is closed on Mondays (and Tuesdays if Monday is a [public holiday](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/how-will-a-public-holiday-in-japan-affect-my-travel-plans/)) and is also closed [during the Japan New Year Period](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/jan-1-3-2024-whats-open-in-tokyo/).) [See more things to do in the Harajuku area with kids here. ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/the-harajuku-omotesando-area-with-kids/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/yoyogi-bubbles-800x800.jpg) Yoyogi Park\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/yoyogi-summer-scooting-800x800.jpg) Yoyogi Park\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/yoyogi-picnic-800x800.jpg) Yoyogi Park\nJust around the corner at the entrance to Yoyogi Park are the **Rockabilly Dancers**. This fascinating insight into Tokyo Subculture is a must see on a Sunday afternoon. This is, by no means, a paid performance but, instead a gathering of a large group of people who share a love for Americana-Happy Days-Soda Pop-Grease Lightning fashion and old school Rock’n’Roll.  \nMy kids love to have a little dance along from the sidelines – their own little rendition.\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/collagerockabilly-800x450.jpg) Rockabilly Dancers\n[**Arisugawa Park, Hiroo**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/arisugawa-park-hiroo/)  \nArisugawa Park is stunning and completely different with every single season.  \nIt has a lovely children’s playground up the top of the hill and a Japanese garden with a large pond down the bottom. It’s perfect for turtle, duck and carp spotting!  \nMore details on this park in my [Hiroo with Kids post here.](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/the-hiroo-area-with-kids/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/05/arisugawa-lucy-hat-800x800.jpg) Arisugawa Park, Hiroo\n**Japanese Gardens**  \nHappo-en is our favourite ‘hidden’ Japanese garden. It’s a famous wedding and shichigosan (children’s coming of age ceremony) venue and is open early in the morning. Entrance to the garden is free and there is a bakery/cafe (with the unfortunate name of “Thrush” for breakfast, tea time and lunch.) This restaurant is also recommended on the **Halal** in Japan website.   \n[I’ve included all the details in my Happoen with kids post here.](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/happoen-a-japanese-garden-in-the-middle-of-tokyo/)\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/happoen-9-800x1000.jpg) Happoen\n**Summer Splash Pads**  \n*Warning; check my post[**here**](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/our-favourite-splash-pads-in-tokyo/) for open times – almost always only open in July & August, regardless of the temperatures.\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/splash-pad-800x800.jpg) Splash Pad, Tokyo\n### You may also enjoy:\n  * [![MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN FOR KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/fun-things-for-kids-with-a-stunning-mt-fuji-backdrop/ \"MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN FOR KIDS\")\n#### [MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN …](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/fun-things-for-kids-with-a-stunning-mt-fuji-backdrop/ \"MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN FOR KIDS\")\n  * [![FOR THAT ANXIOUS PARENT MOMENT: A JAPAN GUIDE](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/for-that-anxious-parent-moment-a-japan-guide/ \"FOR THAT ANXIOUS PARENT MOMENT: A JAPAN GUIDE\")\n#### [FOR THAT ANXIOUS PARENT MOMENT: A JAPAN …](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/for-that-anxious-parent-moment-a-japan-guide/ \"FOR THAT ANXIOUS PARENT MOMENT: A JAPAN GUIDE\")\n  * [![JAPAN FOR PICKY EATERS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/japan-for-fussy-eaters/ \"JAPAN FOR PICKY EATERS\")\n#### [JAPAN FOR PICKY EATERS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/japan-for-fussy-eaters/ \"JAPAN FOR PICKY EATERS\")\n  * [![TRADITIONAL JAPAN IN TOKYO WITH KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/a-more-traditional-japan-without-leaving-tokyo/ \"TRADITIONAL JAPAN IN TOKYO WITH KIDS\")\n#### [TRADITIONAL JAPAN IN TOKYO WITH KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/a-more-traditional-japan-without-leaving-tokyo/ \"TRADITIONAL JAPAN IN TOKYO WITH KIDS\")\n\n\nShare: [](https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/ \"Share on Facebook\")[](https://twitter.com/share?url=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/&text=FREE+THINGS+TO+DO+IN+TOKYO+WITH+KIDS \"Share on Twitter/X\")[](https://pinterest.com/pin/create/link/?url=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/&media=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/happoen-5-year-old-lucy.jpg&description=FREE+THINGS+TO+DO+IN+TOKYO+WITH+KIDS \"Share on Pinterest\")[](https://www.tumblr.com/widgets/share/tool?canonicalUrl=https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/&title=FREE+THINGS+TO+DO+IN+TOKYO+WITH+KIDS \"Share on tumblr\")\n[](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/38763-2/)\n[![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/jan-1-3-2026-whats-open-in-roppongi-tokyo/)\n### Search\n### Popular Posts\n  * [ ![MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN FOR KIDS](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/) MT FUJI VIEWS THAT ARE STILL FUN FOR KIDS ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/fun-things-for-kids-with-a-stunning-mt-fuji-backdrop/)\n  * [ ![WESTERN SUSHI & CALIFORNIA ROLLS IN JAPAN?](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/) WESTERN SUSHI & CALIFORNIA ROLLS IN JAPAN? ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/western-sushi-california-rolls-in-japan/)\n  * [ ![NO, YOU DON’T NEED A WASHING MACHINE IN YOUR JAPANESE HOTEL ROOM](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/) NO, YOU DON’T NEED A WASHING MACHINE IN YOUR JAPANESE … ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/no-you-dont-need-a-washing-machine-in-your-japanese-hotel-room/)\n  * [ ![TEPPANYAKI IN JAPAN: HOW IS IT DIFFERENT TO WHAT YOU MIGHT EXPECT?](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/) TEPPANYAKI IN JAPAN: HOW IS IT DIFFERENT TO WHAT YOU MIGHT … ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/teppanyaki-how-is-it-different-to-what-you-might-expect/)\n\n\n### My Tokyo Chapter\n[ ![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/FullSizeRender-3.jpg) ](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/my-chapters/)[](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/my-chapters/)\n[](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/free-things-to-do-in-tokyo-with-kids/#top)\n### SEE WHAT WE’RE UP TO\n[For live updates and adventures, follow me on Instagram.](https://www.instagram.com/thetokyochapter/)\nI love it SO MUCH when families tag me in their instastories too [@thetokyochapter](http://instagram.com/thetokyochapter)\nIt brings me so much joy to hear when I have helped make another family’s Japan holiday easier and more fun!\n[ ![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/Profile-Square-300x309.jpg) ](https://www.instagram.com/thetokyochapter/)\n### Join my mailing list!\nFirst Name\nEmail address: \nLeave this field empty if you're human: \n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/selfie-oiran-300x300.jpg)\n### My blog is written and researched by me!\nPlease note that (with the exception of guest bloggers) my blog is full of original Japan content written and researched by me.Please be sure to ask for permission to repost any of my written content or images.\nCopyright © 2026 The Tokyo Chapter. All Rights Reserved.\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Tokyo-Disneysea-Carousel-The-Tokyo-Chapter-300x300.jpg)\n### HOW TO SAY THANK YOU\nMany of my readers are kind enough to ask how they can help me for helping them with their Japan trip via my blog.  \nThe best way is truly just by telling your friends about me, by tagging me on social media or making purchases via my affiliate links (doesn’t cost you any extra but I do make a small commission if you do.)\n[![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/Geisha-e1721774055352-300x297.jpg)](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/geisha-experiences-with-kids-in-japan/geisha/)\n© 2026 [The Tokyo Chapter](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/)\nWebsite creation by Next Sense Media\nWe are using cookies to give you the best experience on our website.\nYou can find out more about which cookies we are using or switch them off in settings.\nAccept Reject\nClose GDPR Cookie Settings\n![](https://www.thetokyochapter.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/cropped-the-Tokyo-Chapter-Logo-300x300.jpeg)\n  * Privacy Overview\n  * Strictly Necessary Cookies\n\n\n[Powered by GDPR Cookie Compliance](https://wordpress.org/plugins/gdpr-cookie-compliance/)\nPrivacy Overview\nThis website uses cookies so that we can provide you with the best user experience possible. Cookie information is stored in your browser and performs functions such as recognising you when you return to our website and helping our team to understand which sections of the website you find most interesting and useful.\nStrictly Necessary Cookies\nStrictly Necessary Cookie should be enabled at all times so that we can save your preferences for cookie settings.\nEnable or Disable Cookies Enabled Disabled\nEnable All Save Settings\n[×](javascript:void\\(0\\))\n"
